<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-angles-of-depression" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Angles of Depression</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_0cdjjdqt">
            <p xml:id="auto_t8q3dfhm">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_0fz17qmo">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_8b5fnu70">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_y2ltszdy">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_9hsler1z">
                        2.4 Trigonometry 1
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5wy9v67e">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_l5zewjd6">
                        Apply trigonometric ratios to angles of elevation and depression
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_59i7r5xq" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_j8u3ay2b">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_t4td5iyk" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_if0xc3og">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_6ps13amv" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_xidxo43a"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_voj6woyn">
                        <p xml:id="auto_op9ejg0b">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define the angle of depression as the angle measured downward from a horizontal line to an object below. Explain that angles of depression and elevation between the same two points are equal (alternate interior angles).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_0m4t3f3y">
                        <p xml:id="auto_um8pxe88">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Draw diagrams showing angles of depression. Identify the working angle inside the right triangle (<m>90^\circ - \text{angle of depression}</m>). Apply appropriate trigonometric ratios to find unknown distances.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_y12nl3jz">
                        <p xml:id="auto_f867abyb">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving angles of depression such as calculating distances from cliffs, towers, aircraft, and rescue operations.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_ik43ria2">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/trigonometry-1/angles-of-depression.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_jwqcjtt5">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/trigonometry-1/step-by-step-guide_angles-of-depression.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_q1pdxhs7">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_zrjyo4qk">15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_9lfoh1vq">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_e528rxhb">Individual work</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_m0apkpfi">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_7fnrue7h">
                    This hands-on activity helps students understand angles of depression through direct measurement and calculation using clinometers.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_xa9z6igi">
                    <alert>Facilitation Strategy:</alert>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_jpkva61m">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_2qp4omfv"><p xml:id="auto_7ix635gx">Ensure all students have functional clinometers from the previous lesson.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_yasmcg3u"><p xml:id="auto_auymbvwi">Identify safe elevated positions (steps, balconies, small hills). Emphasize safety when climbing.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_3pueb85v"><p xml:id="auto_gtt1qhab">Guide students to select visible ground objects for measurement.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_gj2oghhb"><p xml:id="auto_82jf4p7c">Circulate and ask: <q>What angle did you measure?</q> <q>How will you calculate the distance?</q></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_o8z7kvpv"><p xml:id="auto_nbl64527">Probe: <q>How is angle of depression different from angle of elevation?</q></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_jges4xa0"><p xml:id="auto_vgat2wd8">Students should discover: angle of depression is measured downward from horizontal.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_6dqdjqqr">
                <title>Interactive Exploration</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_klm583df">
                    If you have an Internet connection, show Learners the interactive exploration.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_lov3todh">
        <p xml:id="auto_2i0306v0">
            <m>\textbf{Individual work}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_wt3eswpf">
            <term>What you require:</term> Your homemade clinometer, a ruler or measuring tape, a notebook and pen and a friend (optional, but fun!)
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gbeotobo">
            <ol xml:id="auto_iqztmt1d">
                <li xml:id="auto_4l0u28vj">
                    <p xml:id="auto_m6hu8u4b">
                        Climb up to a higher place like a step, a balcony, or a small hill
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_psycerpm">
                    <p xml:id="auto_eo6gnvkr">
                        Hold the clinometer at eye level, and look through it toward an object on the
                            ground (like a cone, stone, or your friend’s shoes).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_177fmhnd">
                    <p xml:id="auto_r9pnjhg3">
                        Watch the string and record the angle where it crosses the scale. That’s your angle of depression!
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_foh78a7a">
                    <p xml:id="auto_7oiiijgo">
                        Measure the height from your 
                        eyes to the ground (that’s your vertical distance).
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_0842qtrl">
                        Calculate how far the object is from the base of your standing point.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_vusvblw9">
                    <p xml:id="auto_b3w4lcqy">
                        Share and discuss your work with your classmates.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <exploration xml:id="exploration-angle-depression">
        <title>Understanding Angle of Depression</title>
        
        <introduction xml:id="auto_vb8uq7mx">
            <p xml:id="auto_zsdyncyo">
                The <term>angle of depression</term> is formed when an observer looks <em>down</em> at an object. It is always measured from a strictly <term>horizontal line</term> extending from the observer's eye, downward to the line of sight.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_zd66ldcy">
                Because the horizontal line from the observer's eye is parallel to the ground, we can use the geometric rule of <em>alternate interior angles</em> to simplify our calculations. Use the interactive tool below and follow <xref ref="inst-depression" text="custom">the guided steps</xref> to see how this works.
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <figure xml:id="fig-angle-depression-interactive">
            <caption>Interactive: Observer looking down at a target, illustrating Angle of Depression</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="interactive-depression" platform="jsxgraph" width="95%" aspect="16:9" source="jsxgraph/angle-of-depression.js">
                <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-depression" surface="jsxboard" aspect="16:9"/>
                <instructions xml:id="inst-depression">
                    <p xml:id="auto_5jb2sagj">
                        Use the simulation to explore the relationship between height, distance, and the angle:
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_gb4i2z2a">
                        <ul>
                            <li xml:id="auto_1yb26aog">
                                <alert>The Most Common Mistake:</alert> Look at the top angle (in red). Notice that it is drawn strictly <em>outside</em> the main vertical triangle. Why is it incorrect to place the angle of depression between the vertical cliff and the blue line of sight?
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_w30wxi5j">
                                <alert>The Geometry "Cheat Code":</alert> Look at the blue angle at the target on the ground. This is the angle of elevation <em>from</em> the target <em>to</em> the observer. What do you notice about its value compared to the angle of depression? 
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_wm4hb90s">
                                <alert>Change the Altitude:</alert> Drag the Observer (the blue eye) up and down the y-axis to change the height. If the angle remains the same, what happens to the distance of the target on the ground?
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_z3rj3wf2">
                                <alert>Adjust the Angle:</alert> Use the slider to make the angle of depression larger (steeper). Does the target move closer to the base of the cliff or further away? 
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
    </exploration>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_cmm6pjae">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_fawe73ch">10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_xy7oymor">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_pwiyxodf">Whole class</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_h0eosjoc">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_pss9tru1">
                    After students have explored through the anchor activity, formalize their discoveries about angles of depression.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_fmligsih">
                    <alert>Common Misconception:</alert> <q>Angle of depression is measured from the object.</q> <alert>Correction:</alert> It is measured from the horizontal line at the observer's eye level, looking DOWN.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_1ne77c8m">
        <p xml:id="auto_qpmfc5bk">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_2honm1f8">
                    <p xml:id="auto_wnm4uetk">
                        <term>Definition of Angle of Depression</term>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_7r9cvgqr">
                        The angle of depression is the angle measured downward from a horizontal line to an object below. It is how far your head must tilt from eye-level to look down at an object.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zuc03agu">
                    <p xml:id="auto_62ib63dl">
                        <term>Relationship Between Angles of Elevation and Depression</term>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_otf56o6q">
                        When you look down from a higher point at an object, you form an angle of depression. From the object looking up at you, that forms an angle of elevation. These two angles are equal due to alternate interior angles formed by parallel horizontal lines.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ycp1vq9x">
                    <p xml:id="auto_7m9wg0ng">
                        <term>The Horizontal Reference Line</term>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_rv4zlwoy">
                        The angle of depression is always measured from a horizontal line (eye level when looking straight ahead). The horizontal line is parallel to the ground.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5vs5znev">
                    <p xml:id="auto_9up4c54p">
                        <term>Using Trigonometry with Angles of Depression</term>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_vo0ljwty">
                        To solve problems involving angles of depression:
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_1zgy25ka">
                        <ol marker="Step 1:">
                            <li xml:id="auto_wlqq32yn">
                                <p xml:id="auto_t5bdpyit">
                                   Draw a diagram showing the situation with a right triangle 
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_7so1brwg">
                                <p xml:id="auto_7tvtkrkq">
                                    Identify the angle of depression from the horizontal line
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_s9qpw1w0">
                                <p xml:id="auto_nggj6kvo">
                                    Find the corresponding angle inside the right triangle (often <m>90^\circ -</m> angle of depression, or use alternate interior angles)
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_3hpd023v">
                                <p xml:id="auto_mtze8hpo">
                                    Identify which sides are opposite, adjacent, and hypotenuse relative to your working angle
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_wkxpi00l">
                                <p xml:id="auto_zzsykzko">
                                    Choose the appropriate trigonometric ratio (<m>sin, cos</m>, or <m>tan</m>)
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_p2373ljn">
                                <p xml:id="auto_gf43a4ha">
                                    Solve for the unknown distance or height
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zbudxpbm">
                    <p xml:id="auto_2mnl9yaw">
                        <term>Common Strategy</term>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_uv5vxrsn">
                        For angles of depression problems:
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_amv3t8gn">
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li xml:id="auto_358rmj8r">
                                <p xml:id="auto_v0ewct9j">
                                   The vertical height is often given (height of building, cliff, tower) 
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_6xgq57m7">
                                <p xml:id="auto_znskeq33">
                                    The horizontal distance is often unknown
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_rgnbv632">
                                <p xml:id="auto_wa1g6w6n">
                                    Use tan ratio: <m>tan</m>(angle) <m>= \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{adjacent}}</m>  
                                </p>                           
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_hahumsk0">
                                <p xml:id="auto_ik4rp82x">
                                    Rearrange to find the unknown side
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_fkosw013">
                    <p xml:id="auto_7abke32j">
                        <term> Real-World Applications</term>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_8jbxh8l9">
                        Angles of depression are used in:
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_96njxxht">
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li xml:id="auto_ro0h5ev5">
                                <p xml:id="auto_ldigrdy4">
                                    <term>Aviation:</term> Pilots calculating descent angles to runways
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_axddnw05">
                                <p xml:id="auto_zktpev7t">
                                     <term>Maritime:</term> Lighthouse keepers determining distances to ships
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_4h2m7dg0">
                                <p xml:id="auto_72w17kfw">
                                    <term>Surveying:</term> Measuring depths of valleys or wells
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_4pq4cl3y">
                                <p xml:id="auto_v2bxvu46">
                                    <term>Rescue operations:</term> Helicopters locating people on the ground
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_79g9kmb5">
                                <p xml:id="auto_9y8bxm1j">
                                    <term>Architecture:</term> Determining sight lines from elevated structures
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>
     <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_n7bvb41h">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_prfe3xhl">15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_dv6t4nze">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_q78tzfv3">Individual work, then compare with a partner</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_unf7gga3">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_xscj8fja">
                    Work through the textbook example on the board step by step. Emphasize drawing the diagram first, labelling the angle of depression, identifying the working angle inside the triangle, and then selecting the correct trigonometric ratio.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

        <example xml:id="auto_3otryzal">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_0xdn8vn2">
                A hiker stands on top of a hill that is <m>120\,\text{m}</m> high 
                and looks down at a cabin in a valley. The angle of
                depression to the cabin is <m>40^\circ</m>. 
                Calculate the horizontal distance from the hiker 
                to the cabin.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_2cly5n39">
                Consider the figure below:
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="depression-cabin-example">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Using polar coordinates for exact 40° depression angle
                    % Hiker position: horizontal = 4/tan(40°) from cabin, height = 4
                    \pgfmathsetmacro{\hikerdist}{4/tan(40)}
                    \coordinate (hiker) at (\hikerdist,4);
                    \coordinate (cabin) at (0,0);
                    % Ground line
                    \draw[very thick] (-0.5,0) -- (5.5,0);
                    % Hill at hiker position
                    \draw[very thick, brown] (\hikerdist,0) -- (hiker);
                    \fill[brown!30] (\hikerdist-0.5,0) -- (hiker) -- (\hikerdist+0.5,0) -- cycle;
                    % Hiker at top of hill
                    \draw[thick] (hiker) -- ++(0,0.4);
                    \draw[thick,fill=cyan] ($(hiker) + (0,0.4)$) circle (0.12);
                    \node[above] at ($(hiker) + (0,0.55)$) {Hiker};
                    % Cabin at origin
                    \draw[thick, brown, fill=brown!40] (0,0) rectangle (0.5,0.35);
                    \draw[thick, brown] (0,0.35) -- (0.25,0.5) -- (0.5,0.35);
                    \node[below] at (0.25,-0.1) {Cabin};
                    % Horizontal line from hiker
                    \draw[dashed, thin] (hiker) -- (-0.3,4);
                    % Line of sight using polar: from hiker at -40° (depression)
                    \draw[very thick, dashed, blue] (hiker) -- ($(hiker) + (-150:6)$);
                    % Angle of depression - exactly 40° below horizontal
                    \draw ($(hiker) + (180:1)$) arc[start angle=180, end angle=220, radius=1cm];
                    \node at ($(hiker) + (200:1.4)$) {$40^\circ$};
                    % Right angle mark at base
                    \draw (\hikerdist-0.3,0) -- (\hikerdist-0.3,0.3) -- (\hikerdist,0.3);
                    % Labels
                    \node[below] at (2.4,0) {$d = ?$};
                    \node[right] at ($(hiker) + (0.15,-2)$) {$120\,\text{m}$};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
            </image>
            <p xml:id="auto_97qz6i8w">
                The angle of depression is <m>40^\circ</m>. Inside the right triangle at the hiker's position, 
                the angle between the line of sight and the vertical is <m>90^\circ - 40^\circ = 50^\circ</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_5b4vjf41">
                Using this angle, the horizontal distance <m>d</m> is opposite and the height <m>120\,\text{m}</m> is adjacent.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_9z0mzysy">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \tan\,50^\circ \amp = \frac{d}{120} </mrow>
                    <mrow> d \amp = 120 \times \tan\,50^\circ </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 120 \times 1.1918 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 143\,\text{m}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

