                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_v9y69iac">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_dsr2qyql"><p xml:id="auto_5o8zhr82">Height of tower (opposite) = <m>25\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_c4h0gv6o"><p xml:id="auto_vpmpuk3n">Horizontal distance (adjacent) = <m>80\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_kr516yhz"><p xml:id="auto_5ftrdr46">Angle of depression = <m>\theta</m></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_yzupis6m">
                    Using tangent:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_n34utlzr">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\tan\,\theta \amp = \frac{25}{80}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\tan\,\theta \amp = 0.3125</mrow>
                        <mrow>\theta \amp = \tan^{-1}(0.3125)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 17.35^\circ</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_vezh79zq">
                    The angle of depression is approximately <m>17.4^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-diver-angle">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_26cw7efh">
                    A diver stands on a diving board that is <m>10\,\text{m}</m> above the surface of the 
                    swimming pool. From where she stands, she can see a coin at the bottom of the pool. 
                    The coin is <m>6\,\text{m}</m> horizontally from a point directly below her. 
                    If the pool is <m>3\,\text{m}</m> deep, find the angle of depression from the 
                    diver to the coin.
                </p>
                <image width="55%">
                <latex-image label="exercise-diver-angle">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                        % Scale: 1 unit = 1m for accurate proportions
                        % Diver: 10m above water, Pool: 3m deep, Horizontal: 6m
                        % Water surface at y=0, pool bottom at y=-3, diver at y=10
                        \coordinate (diver) at (0,10);
                        \coordinate (water) at (6,0);
                        \coordinate (coin) at (6,-3);
                        % Pool sides
                        \draw[very thick, brown] (-1,0) -- (8,0);
                        \fill[blue!30] (-0.5,-3) rectangle (7,0);
                        \draw[very thick] (-0.5,-3) -- (7,-3);
                        % Diving board
                        \draw[very thick, gray] (-1,10) -- (1,10);
                        \draw[very thick, gray] (-0.5,0) -- (-0.5,10);
                        % Diver
                        \draw[thick,fill=cyan] (diver) circle (0.2);
                        \node[above] at (0,10.3) {Diver};
                        % Horizontal line from diver
                        \draw[dashed] (diver) -- (7.5,10);
                        % Line of sight to coin
                        \draw[very thick, dashed, red] (diver) -- (coin);
                        % Coin
                        \fill[yellow!70!orange] (coin) circle (0.25);
                        \node[below right] at (6,-3.3) {Coin};
                        % Angle of depression (actual angle is approx 65.2°)
                        \draw ($(diver) + (0:1.5)$) arc[start angle=0, end angle=-65.2, radius=1.5cm];
                        \node at ($(diver) + (-32:2.2)$) {$\theta = ?$};
                        % Labels
                        \node[left] at (-0.7,5) {$10\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[left] at (-0.3,-1.5) {$3\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[below] at (3,0) {$6\,\text{m}$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_ghqdrfvj">
                    Given:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_bim8l4cl">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_k6xhy873"><p xml:id="auto_t6zjj94p">Height of diving board above water = <m>10\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_lkt8xw0z"><p xml:id="auto_chjcw9sr">Depth of pool = <m>3\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_8xmp5tdl"><p xml:id="auto_whdj4pr5">Total vertical distance = <m>10 + 3 = 13\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ru6tct6o"><p xml:id="auto_igqtjp0m">Horizontal distance = <m>6\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_9iseh7cl">
                    Using tangent:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_liwidfux">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\tan\,\theta \amp = \frac{13}{6}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\tan\,\theta \amp = 2.1667</mrow>
                        <mrow>\theta \amp = \tan^{-1}(2.1667)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 65.22^\circ</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_0aglgccn">
                    The angle of depression from the diver to the coin is approximately <m>65.2^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table xml:id="auto_cgbteg35">
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide pre-drawn diagrams with labelled parts. Create a step-by-step checklist for solving problems. Use colour coding: horizontal line in one colour, angle of depression in another. Provide trigonometric ratio reference cards. Allow use of calculators for all calculations.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Complete all practice problems as described. Practice identifying which angle to use inside the right triangle. Draw their own diagrams from word problems.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Solve reverse problems (finding angles given distances). Explore problems involving both angles of elevation and depression. Calculate angles of depression for multiple objects from the same elevated point. Design their own angle of depression problems for classmates.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

